There are many server-side languages and frameworks that can be used to process and store user inputted text from an HTML form. Here are a few popular options:

**Server-side languages:**

1. **PHP**: A mature and widely-used language that is well-suited for web development.
2. **Python**: A versatile language that is popular for web development, data analysis, and machine learning.
3. **Ruby**: A language that is known for its simplicity and ease of use, and is often used with the Ruby on Rails framework.

**Frameworks:**

1. **Node.js**: A JavaScript runtime that allows developers to build fast and scalable server-side applications.
2. **Django**: A high-level Python framework that provides an architecture, templates, and APIs for building web applications.
3. **Express.js**: A lightweight Node.js framework that provides a flexible way to build web applications.

**Example using PHP and MySQL:**

Here's an example of how you might use PHP and MySQL to process and store user inputted text from an HTML form:
```php
// index.php (HTML form)
<form action="process.php" method="post">
  <label for="username">Username:</label>
  <input type="text" id="username" name="username" required>
  <br>
  <label for="email">Email:</label>
  <input type="email" id="email" name="email" required>
  <br>
  <label for="password">Password:</label>
  <input type="password" id="password" name="password" required>
  <br>
  <button type="submit">Submit</button>
</form>

// process.php (server-side script)
<?php
  // Connect to the database
  $servername = "localhost";
  $username = "username";
  $password = "password";
  $dbname = "mydatabase";

  // Create a connection
  $conn = new mysqli($servername, $username, $password, $dbname);

  // Check connection
  if ($conn->connect_error) {
    die("Connection failed: " . $conn->connect_error);
  }

  // Process the form data
  $username = $_POST["username"];
  $email = $_POST["email"];
  $password = $_POST["password"];

  // Insert the data into the database
  $sql = "INSERT INTO users (username, email, password) VALUES ('$username', '$email', '$password')";
  if ($conn->query($sql) === TRUE) {
    echo "New record created successfully";
  } else {
    echo "Error: " . $sql . "<br>" . $conn->error;
  }

  // Close the connection
  $conn->close();
?>
```
**Example using Node.js and Express.js:**

Here's an example of how you might use Node.js and Express.js to process and store user inputted text from an HTML form:
```javascript
// index.html (HTML form)
<form action="/process" method="post">
  <label for="username">Username:</label>
  <input type="text" id="username" name="username" required>
  <br>
  <label for="email">Email:</label>
  <input type="email" id="email" name="email" required>
  <br>
  <label for="password">Password:</label>
  <input type="password" id="password" name="password" required>
  <br>
  <button type="submit">Submit</button>
</form>

// server.js (server-side script)
const express = require("express");
const app = express();
const mysql = require("mysql");

// Connect to the database
const db = mysql.createConnection({
  host: "localhost",
  user: "username",
  password: "password",
  database: "mydatabase"
});

// Process the form data
app.post("/process", (req, res) => {
  const username = req.body.username;
  const email = req.body.email;
  const password = req.body.password;

  // Insert the data into the database
  const sql = "INSERT INTO users (username, email, password) VALUES (?, ?, ?)";
  db.query(sql, [username, email, password], (err, results) => {
    if (err) {
      console.log(err);
    } else {
      res.send("New record created successfully");
    }
  });
});

// Start the server
app.listen(3000, () => {
  console.log("Server started on port 3000");
});
```
These are just a few examples of how you might use server-side languages and frameworks to process and store user inputted text from an HTML form. The specific implementation will depend on your needs and the requirements of your project.
